== Instructions

The has_method method will generate setter and getter methods for each String or Text attribute in the model
To set the translation of a model attribute use the attribute_name_t method
  
  @product.name = "Blue mittens"
  @product.description = "Very comfy blue mittens.  On sale!"
  @product.save
  
  # Spanish
  @product.name_t(:es, "Guantes azules")
  @product.description_t(:es, "Guantes azules muy comfortables.  En venta!")
  
  # French
  @product.name_t(:fr, "Mitaines bleues")
  @product.description_t(:fr, "Mitaines bleues très confortables. En vente!")
  
To return the a model attribute translation use the t_attribute_name method passing it the language abbreviation
  
  @product.t_name(:es)
  => "Guantes azules"
  
  @product.t_description(:fr)
  => "Mitaines bleues très confortables. En vente!"
  
If the language abbreviation isn't set as a parameter, it will use the native_language by default.
  
  class Product < ActiveRecord::Base
    has_accent :native_language => :en
  end
  
  @product.t_name
  => "Blue Mittens"
    
  
== Translation Queue

Everytime to try to access an attribute-language combo that does not currently exists, it sets it to the current model value (not the native language) and adds it to a translation queue.  You can view this queue by using the needs_translation instance method, which returns a hash of attribute-lang combos that need translation.
  
  # User tries to access the German translation
  @product.t_name(:de)
  => "Blue mittens"
  
  @product.needs_translation
  => {'name' => 'de'}
  
Once you set the translations, it gets removed from the queue

  @product.name_t(:de, "Blaue handschuhe")
  @product.needs_translation
  => []
  
Setting a translation to an empty string adds it back to the queue
  
  @product.name_t(:de, "")
  @product.needs_translation
  => {'name' => 'de'}


